		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Aum</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">This article is about the mystical syllable.  For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/AUM" title="AUM">AUM</a>.</div>
<div class="dablink">"Om" redirects here. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Om_(disambiguation)" title="Om (disambiguation)">Om (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="dablink">"Omkara" redirects here. For the Hindi film, see <a href="/wiki/Omkara_(film)" title="Omkara (film)">Omkara (film)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:152px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Aum_red.svg" class="image" title="Devanagari Aum"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Aum_red.svg/150px-Aum_red.svg.png" width="150" height="125" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Aum_red.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Devanagari" title="Devanagari">Devanagari</a> <i>Aum</i></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:152px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Tamil_om.png" class="image" title="The symbol Aum in the Tamil script"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Tamil_om.png/150px-Tamil_om.png" width="150" height="161" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Tamil_om.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The symbol Aum in the Tamil script</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:122px;"><a href="/wiki/File:TibAum.png" class="image" title="The symbol Aum in Tibetan script"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/66/TibAum.png" width="120" height="140" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:TibAum.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The symbol Aum in <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_script" title="Tibetan script">Tibetan script</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><i><b>Aum</b></i> (also <b>Om</b>, written in <a href="/wiki/Devanagari" title="Devanagari">Devanagari</a> as <span style="font-size:125%;" class="Unicode" lang="inc-Deva" xml:lang="inc-Deva">ॐ</span>, in <a href="/wiki/Chinese_character" title="Chinese character">Chinese</a> as <span style="font-size:125%;" class="Unicode" lang="und-Hant" xml:lang="und-Hant">唵</span>, in <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_script" title="Tibetan script">Tibetan</a> as <span style="font-size:125%;" class="Unicode" lang="bo-Tibt" xml:lang="bo-Tibt">ༀ</span>, in <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>&#160;known as <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">praṇava</span></i> or <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">omkāra</span></i>) is a mystical or sacred <a href="/wiki/Syllable" title="Syllable">syllable</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Indian_religions" title="Indian religions">Indian religions</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hinduism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jainism" title="Jainism">Jainism</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a>. The <i>omkara</i> is taken as a <a href="/wiki/Name_of_God" title="Name of God" class="mw-redirect">name of God</a> in <a href="/wiki/Arya_Samaj" title="Arya Samaj">Arya Samaj</a>.</p>
<p>It is pronounced as a <a href="/wiki/Long_vowel" title="Long vowel" class="mw-redirect">long or over-long</a> <a href="/wiki/Nasalized" title="Nasalized" class="mw-redirect">nasalized</a> <a href="/wiki/Close-mid_back_rounded_vowel" title="Close-mid back rounded vowel">close-mid back rounded vowel</a> (<a href="/wiki/IPA" title="IPA" class="mw-redirect">IPA</a>&#160;<span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[oːⁿ]</span>).</p>
<p>It is placed at the beginning of most <a href="/wiki/Hindu_text" title="Hindu text" class="mw-redirect">Hindu texts</a> as a sacred exclamation to be uttered at the beginning and end of a reading of the <a href="/wiki/Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedas</a> or previously to any prayer or <a href="/wiki/Mantra" title="Mantra">mantra</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Mandukya_Upanishad" title="Mandukya Upanishad">Mandukya Upanishad</a> is entirely devoted to the explanation of the syllable.</p>
